answers.body_markdown:
You will need to write your own `Comparator` which parses strings containing numbers with thousands separators as integers, and recognises your special values `Error` and `Unknown`.

This answer makes some simplifying assumptions:
1. All your numbers are positive, so we can use `-1` and `-2` as sentinel values for `Unknown` and `Error`.
1. All your numbers are integers.
1. We explicitly use the `US` `Locale`, so only `,` as a thousands separator will work.

```
import java.text.NumberFormat;
import java.text.ParseException;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Comparator;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Locale;

public class ComparatorExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] data = {&quot;Unknown&quot;, &quot;Error&quot;, &quot;13,125&quot;, &quot;65,029&quot;, &quot;280,552&quot;, &quot;281,012&quot;, &quot;987,072&quot;, &quot;988,775&quot;, &quot;1,250,203&quot;, &quot;2,363,356&quot;, &quot;4,042,563&quot;};
        List&lt;String&gt; sortValues = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(data));
        sortValues.sort(new MyComparator());
        System.out.println(sortValues);
    }
}

class MyComparator implements Comparator&lt;String&gt; {
    NumberFormat format = NumberFormat.getNumberInstance(Locale.US);

    @Override
    public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
        try {
            int n1 = value(o1);
            int n2 = value(o2);
            return n1 - n2;
        } catch (ParseException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }

    private int value(String v) throws ParseException {
        if (v.equals(&quot;Unknown&quot;)) {
            return -1;
        } else if (v.equals(&quot;Error&quot;)) {
            return -2;
        } else {
            return format.parse(v).intValue();
        }
    }
}
```

This is a relatively expensive `Comparator`, as it parses strings into numbers every time it does the comparison.

A more efficient approach would be to do a single pass through the `List`, counting the occurrences of `Unknown` and `Error`, and putting any integers into a `List&lt;Integer&gt;` which is then sorted.

The difference would only be noticeable with large numbers of strings -- perhaps tens of thousands.

