    try {
    	List&lt;Callable&gt; callableList = List.of(
    		() -&gt; doSomething(),
    		() -&gt; doSomething(),
    		// ...
    		() -&gt; doSomething());
    
    	callablesList.parallelStream().forEach(callable -&gt; {
    		try {
    			callable.call();
    		} catch (Exception e) {
    			throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage());
    		}
    	});
    } catch (Exception e) {
    	throw new Exception(e.getMessage());
    } 

This allows me to not have lambdas within lambdas and it allows me to pass the `RuntimeException` to the top level (including the message) and then throw a checked `Exception`. 

Of course to note if one callable has an exception it doesn&#39;t stop the others because that code is in a parallel stream. If it was just a stream it would stop any further processing.

I&#39;ve created two projects specific for `IOException` and `SQLException` (because those are the ones I encountered the most). However, I later found https://github.com/pivovarit/throwing-function. With just a single static import you could have done this:

