answers.body_markdown:
The problem is that the index in `input.codePointAt(i)` is not a codepoint index but a `char` index and emojis are encoded as to `char`s (high and low surrogate). For these codepoints you need to increase the index by two.

You could rewrite your code as:

    public String truncate(String input) {
        int[] arr = new int[5];
        for(int i = 0, j = 0; i &lt; arr.length &amp;&amp; j &lt; input.len; i++){
            arr[i] = input.codePointAt(j);
            j += Character.charCount(arr[i]);
            System.out.println(arr[i]);
        }
        return new String(arr, 0, arr.length);
    }

This however has a problem if `input` has less than 5 codepoints. An improved version would be

    public static String truncate(String input) {
        int[] arr = new int[5];
        int i, j;
        for(i = 0, j = 0; i &lt; arr.length &amp;&amp; j &lt; input.length(); i++){
            arr[i] = input.codePointAt(j);
            j += Character.charCount(arr[i]);
            System.out.println(arr[i]);
        }
        return new String(arr, 0, i);
    }


Or you code use the `codePoints()` stream:

    public String truncate(String input) {
        int[] arr = input.codePoints().limit(5).toArray();
        return new String(arr, 0, arr.length);
    }

----
**Edit**: note that while this solves your problem with emojis it is still not a complete solution as this ignores [graphemes clusters ](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39869673/what-is-a-graphemecluster-and-what-does-expressiblebyextendedgraphemeclusterlite).

If you need to support grapheme clusters you have two possibilities.

When using Java 9 and later you can use the grapheme support added to regular expressions (as shown in a comment to your post).

    public String truncate(String input) {
        return input.replaceFirst(&quot;(\\X{5}).*&quot;, &quot;$1&quot;);
    }

When using Java 20 and later you can take advantage of the added support for extended grapheme clusters in `BreakIterator` (adapted from https://stackoverflow.com/a/76109241).

    public static String truncate(String input) {
        BreakIterator bi = BreakIterator.getCharacterInstance();
        bi.setText(input);
        return input.substring(0, bi.next(5));
    }

I currently don&#39;t have any measurements to tell which of these two solutions is faster.

