According to [documentation][1] you can provide the custom message in the json schema itself but not in the way you did.

For example if you have JSON schema like this ( with default message) :

    {
      &quot;type&quot;: &quot;object&quot;,
      &quot;properties&quot;: {
        &quot;firstName&quot;: {
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;string&quot;,
          &quot;description&quot;: &quot;The person&#39;s first name.&quot;
        },
        &quot;foo&quot;: {
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;array&quot;,
          &quot;maxItems&quot;: 3
        }
      }
    }

You can customize the error messagge by changing above JSON schema as follows:

    {
      &quot;type&quot;: &quot;object&quot;,
      &quot;properties&quot;: {
        &quot;firstName&quot;: {
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;string&quot;,
          &quot;description&quot;: &quot;The person&#39;s first name.&quot;
        },
        &quot;foo&quot;: {
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;array&quot;,
          &quot;maxItems&quot;: 3
        }
      },
      &quot;message&quot;: {
        &quot;maxItems&quot; : &quot;MaxItem must be 3 only&quot;,
        &quot;type&quot; : &quot;Invalid type&quot;
      }
    }


In the message field users can declare their custom message. The key should be the validation type, and the value should be the custom message.

    &quot;message&quot;: {
        [validationType] : [customMessage]
      }

Also, we can make format the dynamic message with properties returned from [ValidationMessage.java][2]class such as arguments, path e.t.c.

Take a look at the [PR][3]



  [1]: https://github.com/networknt/json-schema-validator/blob/master/doc/cust-msg.md
  [2]: https://github.com/networknt/json-schema-validator/blob/master/src/main/java/com/networknt/schema/ValidationMessage.java
  [3]: https://github.com/networknt/json-schema-validator/pull/438


With this setup, this line of code:

     for (ValidationMessage error : errors) {
            System.out.println(error.getMessage());
        }

Should print your customized error message.

