# `switch` expressions

In Java 14+ use [switch expressions][1] to make your intentions more clear. 

```java
  public List&lt;Competition&gt; getCompetitionss( final String competAge ) {
    return
        switch ( competAge )  {
            case COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 -&gt; List.of( … ) ;
            case COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 -&gt; List.of( CompetitionRoller ) ;
            default -&gt; List.of() ;
        }
    }
  }
```

But this would be only imperceptibly faster to execute, if at all. The real benefit is making the code crystal clear to the reader. 

If you really want to optimize, consider establishing those `List` objects just once, outside your method. But even that will not help performance if the compiler were to make that optimization itself (I don’t know if it does or not). 

Beware of premature optimization. Your Question’s code is *highly* unlikely to impact your app’s performance. 

## Example code

Define an enum for your `Competition` objects.

```java
package work.basil.example.competition;

public enum Competition { NATATION , FOOT , HAND , ROLLER }
```

Define the class with your logic. 

```java
package work.basil.example.competition;

import java.util.List;

public class CompetitionEx
{
    public static final String COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 = &quot;compet1&quot;;
    public static final String COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 = &quot;compet2&quot;;

    public List &lt; Competition &gt; getCompetitions ( final String competAge )
    {
        return
                switch ( competAge )
                {
                    case COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 -&gt; List.of ( Competition.NATATION , Competition.FOOT , Competition.HAND , Competition.NATATION );
                    case COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 -&gt; List.of ( Competition.ROLLER );
                    default -&gt; List.of ( );
                };
    }
}
```

Exercise that logic with an `App` class.

```java
package work.basil.example.competition;

public class App
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        App app = new App ();
        app.demo();
    }

    private void demo ( )
    {
        CompetitionEx compEx = new CompetitionEx () ;
        System.out.println ( compEx.getCompetitionss ( CompetitionEx.COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 ) );
        System.out.println ( compEx.getCompetitionss ( CompetitionEx.COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 ) );
    }
}
```

Results:

```none
[NATATION, FOOT, HAND, NATATION]
[ROLLER]
```

# Define lists ahead of time

If you *really* want to optimize, move the list instantiations to an earlier time, to happen once instead of happening on each method call. 

I do not know for sure if this is a real optimization, as the compiler could theoretically optimize those hard-coded `List.of` calls.

I trust you would devise better names than `COMP_LIST_LONG` and `COMP_LIST_SHORT`.

```java
public class CompetitionEx
{
    public static final String COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 = &quot;compet1&quot;;
    public static final String COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 = &quot;compet2&quot;;

    public static final List &lt; Competition &gt; COMP_LIST_LONG = List.of ( Competition.NATATION , Competition.FOOT , Competition.HAND , Competition.NATATION );
    public static final List &lt; Competition &gt; COMP_LIST_SHORT = List.of ( Competition.ROLLER );

    public List &lt; Competition &gt; getCompetitions ( final String competAge )
    {
        return
                switch ( competAge )
                {
                    case COMPETITION_AGE_18_30 -&gt; COMP_LIST_LONG;
                    case COMPETITION_AGE_30_40 -&gt; COMP_LIST_SHORT;
                    default -&gt; List.of ( );
                };
    }
}
```

# `Map`

Rather than write your method `getCompetitions`, you could just as well define a `Map` object to pair a list with each of your possible strings.

As for performance, I can&#39;t say specifically. The concrete `Map` implementation returned by `Map.of` is not specified, and may vary by different versions of Java. But I think we can trust its `get` method would be very fast. 

```java
public class CompetitionEx
{
